\par Berlin Morale Report No. 36. (First Half of January.)
\par 
\par 1. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10956958 GENERAL ATMOSPHERE AND MORALE }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6300646 
\par 
\par The general outlook of the Berliners has changed little since the last report in December. The people have little hope that the Berlin question will be settled this y
ear, they think that only a miracle would get them out of their present difficulties. Although many call 1949 the "year of decision", rumours of an "inevitable war in the spring" have died down considerably.
\par On the whole, Berliners show less interest in po
litics at present than they did a few weeks ago, most minds are fully occupied trying to solve the manifold and difficult problems of the winter. An opinion that is frequently voiced is: "First of all, we must get through this winter. Then we can concern 
ourselves with other matters."
\par 
\par Secretary Marshall's resignation was regretted by the majority of Berliners, with whom he was very popular. Although they believe the future American foreign policy is not to be changed, many Berliners have their own ideas on
 the subject. One frequently hears opinions like "We Berliners knew what we had in Marshall, but what his successor will be like remains to be seen."
\par 
\par The prisoner of war problem raised by the Western Powers at the turn of the year and the publication of f
igures and of the notes addressed to the Soviet Union aroused interest among the population of Berlin. The general opinion is that this step, and their attitude towards the prisoners of war in their hands during the past three years) have won the Western 
P
owers much esteem in all sections of the German population. The Soviet reply to the prisoner of war problem is described as a distortion of facts, and particularly harsh words were spoken by the Berliners about the Soviet-licensed German newspapers and br
oadcasts. They said that any German should be ashamed of participating in the spreading of such reports.
\par 
\par Berliners are taking only a remote interest on the situation in Palestine, China and Indonesia. Some said: "Now the whole world will see that it is not
 only the Germans who start wars. Not even UNO will be able to guarantee world peace for an indefinite time."
\par 
\par 2. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10956958 DOMESTIC FUEL AND POWER }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6300646 
\par 
\par Fuel is still the Berliners' greatest worry, and some Berliners\rquote  living at the Sector Borders say they have recently
 registered in the Soviet Sector to obtain coal, wood etc. offered there. They claimed the allocations granted by the Western Powers are by no means sufficient to meet their needs and their Westmark income is too small to allow them to purchase these comm
odities on the Black Market.
\par 
\par Those Berliners interviewed who have registered in the Soviet Sector claim they did so out of dire need and not because of personal convictions.
\par 
\par Very few Berliners are making use of the offer to obtain coal in the Free Shops o
f the Soviet Zone at Potsdam and Babelsberg. This is probable because this offer is not known to the majority of Berliners, those who have made use of this say the Soviet Zone police allow coal bought in the Free Shops to be taken out without objection. I
t is said that the S-Bahn authorities limit the weight to 35 lbs. The price of coal sold in the Free Shops is 1 cwt. for 16.00 - 18.00 Eastmarks.
\par 
\par 3. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10956958 FINANCIAL WORRIES }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6300646 
\par 
\par Financial worries of Berliners caused by the co-existence of two currencies and the general shortage of Western money, have not improved in any way.
\par 
\par The announcement by Western Berlin post offices that in future DM(West) will be demanded for certain charges (telephone rentals, postage fees for money transfers, registered mail and air mail t
o the Western Zones and parcel post), has met with indignant protests from the majority of Berliners. They say the Western Powers should put a stop to this at once, or introduce the DM (West) as sole currency.
\par 
\par An opinion frequently voiced in Berlin concerning the Free Shops in the Soviet Sector and the Soviet Zone is that the SMA is attempting in this way to draw off a large part of the Eastern money from Western Berlin in order to bring down the rate of exchan
ge (at present approx. 3.40 - 3.70 East for 1 DM (West).
\par 
\par 4. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10956958 FOOD }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6300646 
\par 
\par The majority of Berliners say that the food position has improved considerably during the last three months, but there is a widespread rumour that the ration increase granted on November 1st will be cancelled in February or March.
\par 
\par Rations have everywhere been issued promptly.
\par 
\par Many complaints continue to be made about the inadequate allocation of beverages, the bad quality of dried potatoes and monotonous supply of tinned beef. The possibility of buying honey on the January sugar coupons is welcomed by housewives.
\par 
\par Requests were made to include milk powder in the adults' ration.
\par 
\par The tobacco allocations in all three sectors are still considered to be too low and their distribution irregular;
 many Berliners blame the Magistrat for this, they say the distribution of those quantities which are available is unnecessarily delayed by bureaucratic and clumsy distri-bution machinery.
\par 
\par From the French Sector came many complaints about the inadequate supply of soap and washing materials.
\par 
\par 5. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10956958 EMPLOYMENT }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6300646 
\par 
\par In addition to the general employment problems which are partly due to the blockade, a great number of Berliners particularly stressed the difficulties arising for those who have lost their employment i
n the Soviet Sector because of their political convictions, and who, under the present conditions, cannot find new employment in Western Berlin.
\par 
\par Juveniles complained particularly of the shortage of training jobs and of other suitable training possibilitie
s. It was stated, among others for example, that there is no training school for hairdressers in Western Berlin' and that hairdresser apprentices from Western Berlin had to go to the Soviet Sector where great difficulties were put in their way at the trai
ning schools.
\par 
\par Complaints about irregular and slow payments of unemployment benefits remain unchanged. It was stated that on occasion the payments are 4 - 6 weeks in arrears and the unemployed claim they live in poverty as a result.
\par Many employees asked that work books issued by the Nazis should be abolished. Some claim that when visiting the 'Russian Zone or Sector they were interrogated by police regarding their activities (e.g. employees of Military Government, Press, Radio etc.)

\par 
\par The freedom of trade announced for the American Zone by the US Military Government has aroused much interest, particularly on the part of business men. Opinions on this often differ and may best be brought under the following two main denominators:
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid10956958 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6300646 1. One group hopes that freedo
m of the trade will diminish the existing bureaucratic methods and prepare the way for healthy free competition,
\par 
\par 2. The second group fears that freedom of the trade will cause the general standards of craftmanship to be lowered, and that only ruthless business men will benefit.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid6300646 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6300646 
\par 6. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10956958 POLITICS }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6300646 
\par 
\par The average Berliner takes little interest in German Party politics and fre
quently does not understand the reasons for controversies, as for instance those existing between the SPD and the CDU. What matters to them is merely that the parties are anti-Communist, and in most cases this is where their interest in German politics en
ds. A great number of Berliners say that there is little point at the moment in concerning themselves with political feuds, as the parties "cannot do anything until the Occupation Powers have a clear-cut German policy".
\par 
\par The decision taken by the Parliamentary Council at Bonn to recognise the representatives of Berlin as members with equal rights and votes has been received with great satisfaction by large circles of the Berlin population.
\par 
\par 7. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10956958 ATTITUDE TOWARDS THE OCCUPATION POWERS }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6300646 
\par 
\par The Russian attitude tow
ards the prisoner-of-war problem, the tightening of the Berlin blockade by the blocking of all imports from the Soviet Sector and the Soviet Zone and the strict controls and confiscations at the borders of the Western Sectors in connection with this step,
 have further increased the dislike of the Russians in Western Berlin.
\par 
\par The British are criticised on account of the resumption of dismantlings in the British Zone. Whilst the French attitude to the Stolpe affair is still rankling, the Americans are frequen
tly accused of putting profit motives above a real desire to help even in the air lift.
\par 
\par One of the criticisms made is that it is not possible to send German mail or parcels from abroad by air, whilst CARE parcels, which are paid for in dollars, are transp
orted in special planes. In the view of the Germans, similar considerations apply to the flights of German passengers between Berlin and Frankfurt by A.O.A. If Germans have dollars they may buy air tickets without difficulty, whereas people paying in D-Ma
rks often have to wait weeks for an air passage.
\par 
\par The Ruhr statute published in December is little discussed in Berlin. Berliners interested in the Ruhr question said that the British and Americans had been too lenient regarding the French claims, they say 
these claims have been mainly prompted by the desire to eliminate German competition.
\par 
\par 8. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10956958 HOUSING}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6300646 
\par 
\par A great number of houses and flats in Berlin are still not weatherproof and there is a particular shortage of window-glass.
\par 
\par It is of interest that in recent weeks an increasing number of flats has been offered (usually furnished), which are advertised at prices varying from five hundred to three thousand DM (West).
\par 
\par There are many complaints from Berliners that they have great difficulties with the housing offices and that, in particular, the regulations governing removals from one sector to another have an obstructive effect.
\par 
\par 9. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10956958 CLOTHING}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6300646 
\par 
\par Although there 
is a great demand for warm outer clothing, underclothes, footwear and stockings, the Berliners make relatively little use of their valid textile coupons. The reason which is usually given, is that the goods offered are frequently of inferior quality and t
hat the prices are far too high.
\par 
\par 10. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10956958 RADIO AND PRESS }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6300646 
\par 
\par The RIAS Broadcasting Station (in the American Sector) has for some time been severely criticised by the upper classes. They describe it as a typical military station which, in their opinion, displays an increasing lack of objectivity and impartiality.

\par 
\par Ma
ny say that at the present stake of political intrigues the RIAS should inform Berliners on all current matters instead of- merely reproducing in an entirely biased manner, the standpoint of the American Military Government. The only good German broadcast
ing station, they say, is the NWDR which, thanks to the lifting of Military Government censorship, has developed a style of its own and is attracting more and more listeners. 
\par 
\par The same section of people also reject the boycott campaign against cultural ins
titutions in the Eastern Sector (theatres, cinemas etc.) which has been conducted for some time by the US licensed TAGESSPIEGEL. The standard of the TAGESSPIEGEL is said to have deteriorated considerably through the use of such violent propaganda slogans 
as "Keep away from all theatres in the Eastern Sector".
\par 
\par (It should again be pointed out, however, that the views given under 10 are not general, but originate mainly from the Intelligentsia.)
\par 
\par 11. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10956958 BLACK MARKET }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6300646 
\par 
\par A striking factor in the first weeks of January has been a diminishing of Black Market purchases. The reason is that most people have spent their available money at Christmas and the New Year.
\par 
\par Offers of English chocolate and American cigarettes continue to be large. Candles are rather scarce and difficult to obtain.
\par 
